Hidden Glyphs
================
Platform : KUBSTU CTF
Category : Steganography
Points   : 100
Flag     : KubSTU{lsb_3xtr4ct1on_succ3ss}

------------------------------------------------------------------
THE CHALLENGE
------------------------------------------------------------------

We were given a PNG file and told to find a flag hidden within
the least significant bits of the image.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 1 -- QUICK SCAN WITH ZSTEG
------------------------------------------------------------------

When a PNG challenge explicitly mentions LSB, zsteg is the
fastest tool to reach for. It automatically tries every common
LSB embedding scheme and reports anything that looks like text.

    zsteg image.png

zsteg scanned all bit planes and channel combinations and
immediately reported a hit on the b1,rgb,lsb,xy sequence:

    b1,rgb,lsb,xy    .. text: "KubSTU{lsb_3xtr4ct1on_succ3ss}"

Flag found in a single command.

Remember: zsteg notation explained:
    b1        = 1 bit per channel (LSB only)
    rgb       = using all three color channels
    lsb       = reading the least significant bit
    xy        = scanning pixels left to right, top to bottom
This is the most common LSB embedding configuration used in
CTF challenges. It is always the first thing zsteg checks, so
if the flag is there at all, zsteg will find it instantly.

------------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 2 -- UNDERSTAND WHAT WAS FOUND
------------------------------------------------------------------

LSB steganography works by replacing the least significant bit
of each pixel's color value with one bit of hidden data. A pixel
with blue value 200 (11001000 in binary) becomes 201
(11001001) when a 1 bit is embedded, or stays 200 when a 0 bit
is embedded. The visual difference is completely invisible to
the human eye -- one shade of blue that differs by 1 out of 255
is indistinguishable.

The hidden bits are then reassembled in order (left to right,
top to bottom across pixels) to reconstruct the original bytes
of the hidden message.

Remember: LSB steganography cannot be spotted visually. You need
a tool like zsteg, StegSolve, or stegpy to detect it. zsteg is
the fastest for PNGs because it tries all common configurations
automatically and outputs readable text directly. Always run
zsteg as your first command on any PNG steganography challenge
before reaching for heavier tools.

------------------------------------------------------------------
FULL COMMAND SEQUENCE
------------------------------------------------------------------

    zsteg image.png

